This paper deals with solving large-scale regularized linear inverse problems using multiple processors, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. However, the main focus of the paper is on the algorithmic framework and theoretical analysis of approximate message passing (AMP), which is a popular iterative algorithm for solving linear inverse problems. This suggests that the paper is most likely to be classified under cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.LG (Machine Learning), both of which are sub-categories that deal with signal processing and statistical inference. 

Additionally, the paper also discusses the partitioning of matrices column-wise, which is a topic that falls under the sub-field of distributed computing (cs.DC). The use of multiple processors also implies that the paper may be relevant to the sub-field of parallel and distributed computing (cs.PF) or scientific computing (cs.NA). Finally, the paper also presents numerical results that demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed algorithm, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-field of simulation and modeling (cs.SI).
